name: Dom Gaulton
comment:
Good Afternoon,

I am looking to find out roughly how much it would cost to develop an app. I am a web developer so have some understanding of how apps are built but am not able to do so yet and thought if the quote wasn't too much it could be worth it. I need to finalise exactly how the app would work but it is 99% laid out below.

The idea for this iOS app is a photo based treasure hunt linking to Instagram. Once a week a new treasure hunt is pushed to the app with 12 items to find e.g. ‘a crown’. The user clicks on a treasure hunt from the list and they see the 12 items on a list with a ‘found’ button next to each one, at this point a timer starts. When the user finds a crown they click ‘found’ and Instagram loads with iPhone hooks within / through the app, they take a photo and can add an optional caption. I also need non optional #hashtags to be added to the image that can’t be removed. Once this is sent / posted to instagram the app ticks off the crown item (It doesn’t matter if the picture is of a crown or not!). Once they get 12 items the timer stops and that particular treasure hunt is complete. If they don’t find all 12 items within 12 hours the treasure hunt is failed.

Once all items are complete the treasure hunt is over.

The concept is an app with I think 3 tabs and a welcome screen with a count down to the next treasure hunt release;
the first is simply an Instagram gallery feeding in all images from my @username
the second tab shows all hunts with ticks next to the ones the user has completed or crosses next to failed one (can be filtered by date and completed)
If the user clicks on a uncompleted treasure hunt they are asked whether they want to begin - then the 12 items load and the hunt begins (with a 12 hour timer)
If the user clicks on a failed list they can see the images they took and see the names of the items they couldn’t find which ones they failed on
If the user clicks on the completed ones they see all images and how long it took them - if possible we could have a map / timeline of their treasure hunt and a leader board with the ability for them to see the other users photos of the same treasure hunt, perhaps in a different city!
my account with linked social media

I understand that we could have to have a database to i) store the treasure hunts names and items and ii) store if they have taken a photo for an item then cross referencing to a photo ID by using Instagram API... I would not want to store images, that would be left to Instagram.

We would need to sit down to ensure the idea is completely thought out with your knowledge and discuss push notifications and social media ideas too but functionality is, at the moment, as above.

Kind Regards,

name: Geofrey Mutabihirwa
comment:
I am looking on developing a job searching app for the African market that’s I call Ajira. The idea for the App is for the App to do the job searching for job seekers. To essentially eliminate the need for job seekers to constantly be scouring online job boards, classified ads and websites for job openings.  

Looking for work isn’t easy. Job seekers can endure weeks or months of applications, interviews and networking before landing the right gig, especially in sub-Saharan Africa. Online job boards and social media websites can help, but with Ajira you don't have to be chained to your computer to hunt down a new career. With your Android or iPhone and Ajira App, you can look for work from anywhere, be the first to pounce on new openings, and sell yourself to recruiters.
 
Ajira should be rather straightforward job search app. The App will search for jobs for job seekers, and filter the results based on your industry, location, desired salary and more. The advantage to using Ajira is that the service aggregates listings from thousands of sources, including other online job boards, company career pages, newspaper classifieds and more. Ajira App is an aggregation tool that scrapes job listings from a big variety of sources, including other job boards and company websites. The App will search for new openings, filter the results, and rank the results by assigning compatibility percentage based on your needs and preferences.
Ajira will automatically match you with a specific advertised job and assign a matching percentage based on your qualifications and desires. Users can receive alerts on top of their phones to be notified when new suitable jobs appear in a specific category. When Ajira app finds a suitable job and assigns a compatibility match percentage, it will rank and display the jobs accordingly, saving it so you can apply later or apply directly from the app once you've attached your résumé to your account.
 
The app will narrow the search results by type, location and other criteria. The app will also alert you for new listings based on your search criteria, qualifications, locations, etc. The Idea behind Ajira is for the App to do the search for the job seeker.
 
The app will initially be for sub-Saharan Africa, the listing and aggregated results will be localized to the job seekers preferred location. I will provide all the Job search boards, websites and online listings for the app to scan and agreegate results.
 
Localized results, intelligent search result ranking, percentage compatibility matching combined with instant job opening alert will make this app a unique and efficient app for job seekers in sub-Saharan Africa. It will eliminate the need for job seekers to constantly be engaging with online job boards, websites and other apps looking for jobs, the app constantly looks for the most suitable jobs for job seekers.  I am looking on developing this App. Can OpenxCell develop such an app? if so, Could you kindly provide me with your development process and quotation. Thanks.

name: Jonathan Foos
comment:
My name is Jonathan Foos. I co-own a mobile app development company out of Colorado.

We are looking for someone to develop the web back-end for two apps that we are developing. We came across your website because we saw that you are experienced with Parse's system. We'd like to use Parse for the back-end.

Here's what we need -

    We have one mobile app that will be used internally by the Parks department to update information about the local trails. This information includes:
        Trail conditions (open, closed, caution)
        Notes or description about the trail's conditions (if it's muddy, fallen tree, etc.)
        Adding a photo of the trail's condition (if it's rainy, muddy, etc.)
        GPS coordinates of the trailhead
        Marking if a trail is dog-friendly, horse friendly, paved, etc. (Boolean value for each key)

    We will also need an internal website interface to update the same information about the trails (which the Parks department would log into to make changes).

    We will need to create hooks for push notifications, so that each time a trail's status is changed, the update is sent as a push notification to any subscribers of that trail.

    In essence, the mobile app and web interface will be used by the Colorado Parks Department to update the conditions of their trails in realtime. The internal Parks mobile app and web interface will update a list of trails with any changes. This list of trails needs to be presented as a JSON array that can be consumed by the Parks' public website.

    We are also developing a second mobile app for end-users. This app will need to be able to consume the data about conditions of all the trails.

    In addition, the end-user app will also need to allow users to:
        Rate trails
        Add photos of the trail
        Comment on the trail's condition
        Create a user account
        Allow users to add a trail to their favorites and store it on their account
        Allow users to subscribe to push notifications on a trail's condition

Let me know if you need any other information. I'd love to set up a quick chat about all this to make sure it's all clear. I know it's a lot of info!

We are going to develop the mobile apps themselves (the internal parks app, and the end-user app). We would love for you to develop the back-end that drives the apps and data feed for the website.

Let me know asap if you're interested!
